Part A – Theoretical Foundation

1. Statistical Distributions

A statistical distribution describes how the values of a random variable are spread. It shows the probability or frequency of each possible outcome. Common examples include Normal, Binomial, and Poisson distributions.

⸻

2. Q-Q Plot

A Quantile-Quantile (Q-Q) plot is used to compare the distribution of a dataset with a theoretical distribution (usually normal).
	•	If points lie on a straight line → data is normally distributed
	•	Deviations indicate skewness or outliers

⸻

3. Discrete vs Continuous Distributions
	•	Discrete Distribution: Takes countable values (e.g., number of students, number of defects)
	•	Continuous Distribution: Takes infinite values within a range (e.g., height, weight, time)

⸻

4. Bernoulli Distribution

A distribution with only two outcomes:
	•	Success (1) with probability p
	•	Failure (0) with probability 1 − p

Used for single trial experiments.

⸻

5. Binomial Distribution

Represents the number of successes in n independent Bernoulli trials.
Conditions:
	•	Fixed number of trials
	•	Same probability of success
	•	Independent trials

⸻

6. Log-Normal Distribution

A variable is log-normally distributed if its logarithm follows a normal distribution.
	•	Right-skewed
	•	Used in finance, income distribution, stock prices

⸻

7. Power Law Distribution

In this distribution:
	•	Small values are very common
	•	Large values are rare but significant

Examples: wealth distribution, social media followers, earthquake magnitude.

⸻

8. Box-Cox Transform

A mathematical transformation used to:
	•	Make data more normally distributed
	•	Stabilize variance
	•	Improve model performance

⸻

9. Poisson Distribution

Used to model the number of events occurring in a fixed interval.
Examples:
	•	Number of calls per hour
	•	Number of website hits

⸻

10. Z-Score Probability

Z-score tells how far a value is from the mean in terms of standard deviation:
	•	Z > 0 → above mean
	•	Z < 0 → below mean

Used in hypothesis testing and normalization.

11. PDF vs CDF

Function
Meaning
PDF (Probability Density Function)
Probability at a specific value
CDF (Cumulative Distribution Function)
Probability up to a value
